{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0679c8ee4bfe0a31d888af4db37b4b43","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The mock is being called with `mockCalcular` (the actual mock fn) and also returning the result successfully, but in many cases `mockCalcular.mock.calls[0]` is undefined. This means the `calcular` import in the route is NOT the mocked one. \n\nWhy? Because the route file imports from `@akasha/core`, and the test mocks `@akasha/core` using `vi.mock`. But the import path might be resolved differently. The test mocks the package, but the route uses a sub-export. Let me check.\n\nWait, the test file imports `from '@akasha/core'` directly, and the test mocks `@akasha/core`. The route also imports `from '@akasha/core'`. They should be the same module.\n\nBut the issue: The `vi.mock('@akasha/core', ...)` factory is hoisted to the top, but the test imports `import { GET } from '../../../../apps/akasha-portal/src/app/api/akasha/mandato-do-dia/route'`. The route's import is resolved at module load time. When vitest hoists the mock, it should mock the module for the route too.\n\nLet me check if the test is properly capturing the call. Looking at the test output:\n- 5 tests pass (the ones using direct fields)\n- 6 tests fail: \n  - 'retorna 200 com MandatoEsqueleto no shape esperado' — body.mentor_hook mismatch (intencao=buscar paz vs 'claridade')\n  - 'usa intencao default' — `mockCalcular` called 0 times\n  - 4 more with same `mock.calls[0]` undefined\n\nSo the FIRST one (using `mockCalcular` indirectly via `body.mentor_hook` returned in JSON) PASSES in the sense that the body came back successfully. The issue is the `mockCalcular` is the REAL function being called, not the mock. The factory is hoisted but the assignment to `mockCalcular` variable doesn't propagate.\n\nWait, `vi.hoisted` returns the variables to the test scope, but does the vi.mock factory closure have access to them? Let me re-check.\n\nIn `vi.hoisted(() => ({...}))` — these are defined at hoist time. Then `vi.mock('@akasha/core', ...)` is also hoisted. The factory function captures `mockCalcular` from outer scope. Since the hoisted vars are defined before the vi.mock factory runs, the reference should be valid.\n\nBut wait — `vi.hoisted` returns the value, but the closure inside the factory references the variable by name. JavaScript closures resolve at call time. So at the time the mock factory runs, the `mockCalcular` binding should be set.\n\nHmm, let me think differently. The first test `'retorna 200 com MandatoEsqueleto'` calls GET, and `body.mentor_hook.intencao` is `'buscar paz'` not `'claridade'`. This means the REAL `calcular()` was called with the input `'buscar paz'`, and the real function returned a real `mentor_hook` with `intencao: parsed.intencao_inicial` (which was 'buscar paz'). So the real function is being called, not the mock.\n\nThe first test passed for the other 5 assertions, but failed on `mentor_hook` because the REAL calcular returns the real shape but with a real intencao. So `mockCalcular` was never invoked.\n\nWhy? The hoisted variable assignment in test scope is fine, but maybe vitest's hoisting for the `vi.mock` factory works differently when the factory is `async` and uses `vi.importActual`. Let me look at other tests that mock @akasha/core similarly.","signature":"2a27260a8e5b6b3b7b8b0cecae316283c568cb8db450715c20cbc878b72c83bf"}],"model":"MiniMax-M3","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard"},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57d2ecb7-0101-4087-a0d9-0837b2dd3247","uuid":"9d7596e2-75bb-4558-903e-2b304d41e1b0"}
