{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"0679c96b1550c30272a22b1cb86bee2d","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Same issue. The mockCalcular is NEVER called — the real `calcular` is being executed. The mock is NOT being applied. \n\nThe issue is that `vi.mock('@akasha/core', ...)` is being hoisted, but the test is using `vi.hoisted` to define the mock fns, and the closure inside the factory doesn't see them.\n\nWait, let me re-read. In vitest, `vi.hoisted` is hoisted to the very top, BEFORE `vi.mock`. So the order is:\n1. `vi.hoisted` runs → `mockCalcular` is defined\n2. `vi.mock('@akasha/core', () => { ... mockCalcular ... })` runs → factory uses mockCalcular\n3. `import { GET } from '...route'` runs → route's import of `@akasha/core` returns the mock\n\nThe factory should see the hoisted mockCalcular. So why is the real function being called?\n\nLet me check if `vi.hoisted` works the way I think. Maybe the destructuring `const { mockCalcular } = vi.hoisted(...)` is not the same as `const mockCalcular = ...`. Actually, it should be the same — vi.hoisted returns a value, and you destructure or assign.\n\nWait, let me look at the working example from `tests/lib/ai/mapa-insights.test.ts:15`:\n```ts\nconst { mockRedisGet, mockRedisSet, mockCreateChatCompletion } = vi.hoisted(() => ({\n  mockRedisGet: vi.fn<...>(),\n  ...\n}));\n```\n\nSame pattern. So that should work.\n\nHmm. Let me check if maybe the issue is the `mockPrisma` object — when used inside `vi.mock('@/lib/infrastructure/prisma', () => ({ prisma: mockPrisma }))`, vitest serializes. The mock functions inside `mockPrisma` need to be hoisted too — they are, since `vi.hoisted` returns the object with `vi.fn()` calls already made.\n\nLet me try a different debug. Add a `console.log` in the mock factory to see if it runs. Actually, let me try moving the mocks earlier and using simpler structure.\n\nActually wait — I notice that `tests/api/akasha/ritual/route.test.ts` does NOT use `vi.hoisted` and uses simple `vi.mock('@/lib/application/auth/akasha-guard', () => ({ requireAkashaApi: mockRequireAkashaApi }))`. That works (it's been passing). But the test declares `const mockRequireAkashaApi = vi.fn()` BEFORE the mock. Vitest hoists both. That works.\n\nIn my case, I'm using `vi.hoisted` to return the mocks. This should also work — vi.hoisted is the official way to share state between hoisted `vi.mock` factories and the test body.\n\nHmm, but the test for `vi.hoisted` is similar to mapa-insights.test.ts which works. What's different?\n\nLet me re-read my code... \n\n```ts\nconst { mockRequireAkashaApi, mockCalcular, mockPrisma } = vi.hoisted(() => ({\n  mockRequireAkashaApi: vi.fn(),\n  mockCalcular: vi.fn(),\n  mockPrisma: {\n    birthChart: { findUnique: vi.fn() },\n    user: { findUnique: vi.fn() },\n  },\n}));\n```\n\nOK. Then:\n```ts\nvi.mock('@akasha/core', () => ({\n  AkashaInputSchema: {\n    safeParse: (input: unknown) => ({ success: true, data: input }),\n  },\n  calcular: mockCalcular,\n}));\n```\n\nWhen the route imports `calcular` from `@akasha/core`, it should get `mockCalcular`. Let me verify by adding a print.\n\nActually, let me first check the test pattern from one of the other akasha API tests, because they all do the same thing and presumably work:","signature":"8a197a1330e4d7fac3244e2c0ac9739ad4c4bc73ba524c8ac165e8d797f13251"}],"model":"MiniMax-M3","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard"},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"57d2ecb7-0101-4087-a0d9-0837b2dd3247","uuid":"4bbc196b-559d-4461-9ba1-d4a9c5788e9e"}
